Here Shida had suffered neglectful booking for a while, then built up a little, but also recently beaten by Toni Storm, so needed to be reestablished within the match as a serious contender. FTR do a hybrid WWE/classic indie style. It's all about flow and perfecting execution of the individual moves.

>>8376073
Equally talented yes.
Big man can even get away with a hair less talent provided he gets lucky.
A huge, huge part of any fight that people who haven't fought don't understand is controlling the fighting space/ring/cage. If you're bigger that's easier to do because of one simple thing- effective reach.
A big guy with big arms can hit you before you hit him unless you're significantly quicker at both attacking and evading the counterpunch/grapple. Your own effective reach is also distorted because you can't fight as safely at full reach, you have to either start from further back and risk getting read on the rush in, or go ultra aggressive to try get inside their reach which is hard if they have gorilla arms and hamhock fists like Brock. If they're noticeably taller it also alters your effective reach because you're having to angle more to get a head shot, and particularly slows any kind of head kick because you have more distance to travel and are kicking above your own head.
They can afford to be static and expend less energy but still control the space through reach. They can also have much bigger influence on positioning and your own footwork by relatively smaller efforts because of the larger stride.
Size in a fight is not just about strength, weight, or protective bulk. Reach and space control are incredibly important and hard to learn about without fighting.
>t. Former regional and national martial arts competitor and medallist before packing it in due to arthritis and unrelated nerve damage. We trained against the biggest guy in the class specifically to work on reach and space control.
